<chapter xml:id="chapter-syllabus">
  <title>DGHM 110: Introduction to Digital Humanities (Spring 2026)</title>

  <introduction>
    <p>Welcome to Introduction to Digital Humanities! This course will help you gain a fundamental understanding of the digital humanities (DH), focusing on both the “digital” and the “humanities.” You can expect to learn concepts, methods, and tools for working with data such as literary texts, historical maps, and visual art while reflecting on what it means to do so as a humanist.</p>
  </introduction>

  <section xml:id="syl-learning-objectives">
    <title>Learning Objectives</title>
    <p>Upon completion of this course, students will be able to:</p>
    <p>
      <ul>
        <li>Develop an understanding of digital humanities.</li>
        <li>Analyze digital humanities issues through the visualization of quantitative data.</li>
        <li>Apply close- and distant-reading practices to humanities issues.</li>
        <li>Gain awareness of a variety of digital tools and methods, and appropriately select from these.</li>
        <li>Gain a basic understanding of AI and refine prompting techniques.</li>
        <li>Gain awareness of a variety of DH projects that address a variety of humanities issues.</li>
        <li>Practice methods for describing humanities data, including markup languages.</li>
        <li>Communicate analysis of humanities issues through digital platforms.</li>
      </ul>
    </p>
  </section>

  <section xml:id="syl-description">
    <title>Course Description</title>
    <p>Welcome to Introduction to Digital Humanities! This course will help you gain a fundamental understanding of the digital humanities (DH), focusing on both the “digital” and the “humanities.” You can expect to learn concepts, methods, and tools for working with data such as literary texts, historical maps, and visual art while reflecting on what it means to do so as a humanist. We will frequently discuss how the skills you acquire in this course can assist you in future courses as well as help prepare you for a variety of careers after graduation. Particular emphasis will be placed on critically understanding artificial intelligence.</p>
  </section>

  <section xml:id="syl-goals">
    <title>Course Goals, Learning Objectives, and Competencies</title>
    <p>The following are the main goals for the course, along with learning outcomes and career competencies you can expect to develop. Please note that while these are the goals and competencies that we will most explicitly focus on—and associated learning outcomes are included in the course schedule—we will certainly touch on others. Goals and competencies will be addressed through both formal assignments and less formal exercises.</p>
  </section>

  <section xml:id="syl-texts">
    <title>Course Texts and Additional Resources</title>
    <p><em>Required Text:</em> Ahmed Bouchentouf: <em>The Prompt Recipe: A Practical Guide to Prompt Engineering and AI Interaction</em> (breadbooks, 2025)</p>
    <p><em>Optional Text:</em> Johanna Drucker, <em>The Digital Humanities Coursebook: An Introduction to Digital Methods for Research and Scholarship</em> (Routledge, 2021). I have scanned relevant chapters and have made these available through Canvas, but you may choose to purchase a hard copy if you prefer.</p>
    <p><em>Additional course materials:</em> These include online readings, digital tools, and DH projects, which are all freely available online. Links are provided in the syllabus and on our course Canvas site.</p>
  </section>

